---
import ChapterEntry from '../components/blocks/ChapterEntry.astro';
import Prose from '../components/blocks/Prose.astro';
import ComparisonLayout from '../components/blocks/ComparisonLayout.astro';
import Diagram from '../components/blocks/Diagram.astro';
import CascadeVisualization from '../components/blocks/CascadeVisualization.astro';
import VignettePlaceholder from '../components/blocks/VignettePlaceholder.astro';
import ChatPlaceholder from '../components/blocks/ChatPlaceholder.astro';
import type { Chapter } from '../data/chapters';

type Props = Chapter;
const { number, title } = Astro.props;
---

<ChapterEntry
  chapterNumber={number}
  title={title}
  lead="The critical distinction in the system."
/>

<Prose>
  <p>
    Both are modules. Both plug in the same way. But they operate in fundamentally
    different realms, and using the wrong one for a task produces unreliable behavior.
  </p>
</Prose>

<ComparisonLayout>
  <Fragment slot="tools">
    <p>
      <strong>AI-decided.</strong> The model sees tools in its context. It chooses
      when to call them. Visible, intentional.
    </p>
    <p>
      Tools appear in the system prompt. The AI sees each tool's name, description,
      and input schema. When it decides to take an action, it generates a tool call.
      Tool calls and results appear in conversation history — everything is traceable
      and explainable.
    </p>
    <p>Tools extend what the model can do.</p>
  </Fragment>

  <Fragment slot="hooks">
    <p>
      <strong>Code-decided.</strong> The AI has no concept that hooks exist. They
      fire automatically. Invisible to the model.
    </p>
    <p>
      Hooks are not listed in the system prompt. The model cannot see them, cannot
      call them, cannot choose to use them. They operate entirely in the system layer,
      responding to events the AI never sees.
    </p>
    <p>Hooks govern what the model is allowed to do.</p>
  </Fragment>
</ComparisonLayout>

<Diagram
  src="/diagrams/tools-vs-hooks.svg"
  width="wide"
  alt="Side-by-side comparison showing the fundamental difference: AI-visible tools vs AI-invisible hooks"
  caption="Tools are listed in the AI's context. Hooks fire in the system layer, invisible to the model."
/>

<Prose>
  <h2>Tools: the AI decides</h2>

  <p>
    A Tool is an action: read a file, search the web, run a command. Available tools
    are listed in the AI's system prompt. The model sees each tool's name, description,
    and input schema. When it decides to take an action, it generates a tool call:
    <em>"Use <code>read_file</code> with path <code>/src/main.py</code>."</em>
  </p>

  <p>
    The model <em>chooses</em>. It looks at the request, evaluates its options, and
    picks a tool intentionally. Tool calls appear in conversation history. Results
    appear in conversation history. Everything is visible, traceable, and explainable.
  </p>

  <p>Tools extend what the model can do.</p>
</Prose>

<Prose>
  <h2>Hooks: code decides</h2>

  <p>
    Hook Handlers respond to events in the system. When something happens, an event
    fires. Hook Handlers that have registered for that event run automatically. The
    AI model has <em>no idea</em> that hooks exist.
  </p>

  <p>
    Hooks do not appear in the model's instructions. They are not listed in the
    system prompt. The model cannot see them, cannot call them, cannot choose to use
    them. Hooks operate entirely in the system layer.
  </p>

  <p>
    Hooks can observe (logging, analytics), block (safety, compliance), modify (data
    transformation), or inject new context the AI reads on its next turn. In every
    case, the AI doesn't know a hook was involved.
  </p>

  <p>
    The most powerful hook action is <strong>inject_context</strong>: a hook places a
    message into the conversation that the AI reads on its next turn, as if it were
    part of the natural flow. The hook doesn't interrupt the AI — it places information
    where the AI will naturally encounter it, and the AI does what language models do:
    read text and respond to it.
  </p>

  <p>
    Consider the code quality problem. If you give the AI a <code>run_code_checker</code>{' '}
    tool and instruct it to always run it after writing a file, the AI might forget.
    It might decide the check isn't needed this time. That's probabilistic compliance.
    As a hook registered for the <code>tool:post</code> event, the check runs
    automatically every single time, regardless of what the model decides. The error
    is swallowed if the hook itself crashes — the pipeline continues — but the operation
    is blocked only by an explicit <strong>deny</strong>.
  </p>
</Prose>

<CascadeVisualization />

<VignettePlaceholder
  width="wide"
  rationale="Animating the cascade with events flowing through deny/askuser/inject/modify/continue would show how results resolve dynamically — much clearer than static text"
/>

<Prose>
  <h2>Events and dispatch</h2>

  <p>
    Amplifier defines 41 canonical events, organized by namespace. Each event name
    follows a consistent pattern: <code>namespace:action</code>. Session events are
    <code>session:start</code>, <code>session:end</code>. Tool events are{' '}
    <code>tool:pre</code> (before execution), <code>tool:post</code> (after execution).
    Provider events are <code>provider:request</code>, <code>provider:response</code>.
  </p>

  <p>
    Events and hooks are the same system. There is no separate "event bus" and "hook
    registry." It's one unified dispatch mechanism (<code>HookRegistry.emit()</code>)
    that fires an event and collects responses from registered hooks.
  </p>

  <p>
    When a hook handler throws an error, the error is swallowed. The pipeline
    continues. The error is logged, but it doesn't crash the system. Hook errors are
    non-fatal — a crashed logging hook does not stop the tool call. The only hook
    action that stops an operation is an explicit <strong>deny</strong>. Every event
    also gets automatically stamped with the session ID, parent session ID, and a UTC
    timestamp as infrastructure stamps.
  </p>
</Prose>

<ChatPlaceholder
  prompt="Not sure whether something should be a tool or a hook? Ask here."
/>
